President Obama has nominated Patrick A. Burke to serve as U.S. Marshal for the District of Columbia. Burke currently serves as Assistant Chief of Police in the Strategic Services Bureau for the Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia. He has been with the department for over 26 years and has served in various capacities, including overseeing security coordination for major events such as the Presidential Inauguration and the 2008 Papal visit. Burke is also an adjunct professor at The George Washington University, teaching courses in Emergency Management, Crisis Communications, and Media/Public Relations. He holds a B.S. from the State University of New York at Buffalo, an M.S. from Johns Hopkins University, and an M.A. from the Naval Postgraduate Schoolâ€™s Center for Homeland Defense and Security. President Obama praised Burke's long and stellar track record in public safety and expressed confidence in his ability to protect his fellow citizens with unwavering courage and commitment.